diff:1620528552:1620528552:=1,48d0%0a%3c :Category: Varia%0a%3c :Expansion: Filler words in Mandarin and its unfortunate pronunciation%0a%3c :Author: Simon_Y%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.FillerSoundsAndWords|FillerSoundsAndWords]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.albert_l|albert_l]]%0a%3c :Section: A%0a%3c :Completed: 08.05.2021 - 19:49%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Just wanted to add an example of a filler word in Mandarin.%0a%3c %0a%3c "那个" is a filler word in Mandarin, roughly translate to "that". It is pronunced as nàge/nèige in Pinyin, and [nagə] or [negə]. As you may have heard of or realized now, this can be misheard into an undesirable English word.%0a%3c %0a%3c An unfortunate incidence has occured: https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/09/08/professor-suspended-saying-chinese-word-sounds-english-slur%0a%3c This case actually reveals a bigger problem than an incident, as the faculty was suspended. I agree that the speaker should apologize for the incident and clarify that it was unintentional. I would argue that the usage of filler words, as the article points out, is subconscious. Mutual understanding is crucial when building a diverse community, which was not present in this incident.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ref:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filler_(linguistics)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
